<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / The Finance Bill: Labour warns it will give bill rough
passage - Commons Battle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Labour party warned yesterday that its current refusal to co-operate
with Tory whips over the government's legislative programme would give the
finance bill a difficult passage through the House of Commons.
In previous years Labour and Tory whips have agreed to argue over a limited
number of clauses to get the legislation through.
This time the Labour party has withdrawn co-operation with the government on
parliamentary matters, in protest at the speed with which the statutory sick
pay bill was pushed through all its Commons stages last month.
Ms Harriet Harman, shadow chief secretary to the Treasury, said that
government ministers would acquire 'a serious headache' trying to implement
the bill, which at 417 pages will be the largest of this session.
'We are seeking to create difficulties for this bill,' she said. The main
measures Labour plans to oppose are the insurance premium tax, the air
passenger tax, the freezing of personal allowances and the reduction in the
married couples' allowance.
She also claimed that the introduction of a unified Budget in November meant
that the timetable for the finance bill was to the Conservatives'
disadvantage.
Under the old system the finance bill was debated after the implementation
of many of the Budget's measures. But Ms Harman claimed that, on this
occasion, Tory MPs would be asked to vote for tax-raising measures yet to
take effect. 'This will put more pressure on Tory MPs who could rebel,' she
said.
Tory ministers were confident, however, that Labour's policy would pose no
threat to the bill.
Many of the bill's provisions are due to take effect at the start of April
but some were enacted by a resolution at the end of the budget debate last
month.
</TEXT>
