<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / The Finance Bill: Private health market 'may suffer' -
Insurance Premium Tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER and BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The premium tax introduced by the Finance Bill could hinder the growth of
the private health and creditor insurance market at a time when these
sectors are being asked to fill gaps developing in the welfare state,
insurers said yesterday.
Neither line of insurance is among those specifically excluded from the tax,
which will be imposed on most general insurance from next October.
Mr Tony Baker, head of public relations at the Association of British
Insurers, said insurers may press for an amendment to the bill. 'We don't
think health and creditor insurance should be taxable. This will send the
wrong signals to the public.
Mr Julian Ross, product development manager with Prime Health, a specialist
medical insurer, said: 'If the whole philosophy and policy of this
government is to make people more self-reliant, it seems rather stupid to
penalise them for taking out private medical insurance. They are effectively
being double-taxed.' Medical insurers are also searching for a way around
the tax, using the distinction between long-term insurance, such as life
cover, which is exempt from the tax, and general short-term insurance, which
is not.
Bupa, the largest supplier of private medical insurance, has applied to the
Department for Trade and Industry for a licence to write long-term business,
for a subsidiary it is planning to set up this spring. Bupa is considering
using it to write some private medical cover as long-term business, avoiding
the tax.
Norwich Union and PPP, which can already write long-term business in
addition to conventional private medical insurance, are also considering
this option. However, Mr Tim Baker, product development manager with Norwich
Union Healthcare, said there were many complications involved in writing PMI
on a long-term basis. At present, PMI premiums are reviewed once or twice a
year. Insurers have been able to increase premiums steeply to cope with
rising costs and claim levels in the past few years, but if policies were
arranged over longer terms, underwriters would have to be careful to price
them correctly from the start.
There may also be discrepancies in other sectors. Prime Health also offers
long-term care insurance to cover nursing for the elderly, written on an
annually renewable basis, while all its competitors offer cover on a
long-term basis. Unless it obtains an exemption, Prime Health's policies
will be at a competitive disadvantage, as it has no long-term side to which
to switch the business.
Large corporate medical schemes may avoid most of the tax's impact by
unbundling their cover into its constituent parts. Insurance - in the form
of stop-loss cover - accounts for only a tiny proportion of their total
premiums, while the rest is actual hospital costs, administration and so on.
Lines of insurance excluded from the tax include reinsurance, large scale
marine and aviation, and exports.
</TEXT>
