<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / The Finance Bill: Commissioners gain new power -
Confidentiality
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tax commissioners are to be given the power to request information from the
Inland Revenue on a taxpayer's liability to tax to help them in deciding tax
appeals.
The change outlined in the Finance Bill follows similar provision in the
1992 Finance (No 2) Act enabling the Lord Chancellor, Lord Mackay, to make
regulations giving General and Special tax commissioners powers to request
information from taxpayers about their tax affairs.
The move follows concern expressed by the Council on Tribunals, the
government's tribunals watchdog, about the lack of formal procedural rules
for tax appeals.
In 1991 the Council produced a set of model rules, which prompted the Lord
Chancellor's Department and the Inland Revenue to issue a joint consultation
document: Procedural Rules for General and Special Commissioners.
The consultation exercise exposed the need for commissioners to have tougher
powers to request information from both sides to an appeal.
Clause 239 of the bill provides powers for the Lord Chancellor with consent
to make regulations allowing the commissioners to require any party to an
appeal, including the Inland Revenue, to provide information relevant to the
determination of a taxpayer's liability.
The Lord Chancellor is expected to lay the regulations before Parliament
soon.
In the 1992/1993 tax year the general commissioners dealt with 376,695 tax
appeals and the special commissioners heard 45 cases.
</TEXT>
