<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / The Finance Bill: Capital gains boost for trusts -
Collective Funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Investors in gilts through a unit trust will be able to use indexation to
mitigate their capital gains, according to a clause in the finance bill.
Investors in assets exempt from capital gains tax, such as UK government
bonds, are liable to pay the tax when these assets are held in a collective
fund such as a unit trust or offshore fund.
Under clause 89 of the bill, investors in collective funds and building
society shares will be able to offset part of their tax liability through an
indexation allowance based on movements in the retail price index.
Investors will only be able to use this allowance to reduce tax liabilities
on capital gains. In the November Budget the chancellor abolished the use of
indexation to create or increase losses for tax relief.
Mr Simon Smith, taxation adviser at the Association of Unit Trusts and
Investment Funds, welcomed the change. 'We have been lobbying for it for a
long time so it is nice to see it there,' he said.
The bill also removed an anomaly in the treatment of options for capital
gains tax payers, making it no longer disadvantageous to exercise a put
option rather than sell it.
The bill confirms the introduction of the airport departure tax announced in
the November Budget. From October 1 air passengers from the UK will be
charged Pounds 5 for flights to British and European Union destinations and
Pounds 10 for trips elsewhere. Airlines will be responsible for collecting
the duty. Children under two, passengers on aircraft with fewer than 20
seats and those making return journeys in the UK will be exempted.
</TEXT>
