<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / Home office telecoms staff opt to strike on Monday
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Home Office staff employed in its telecommunications installation and
maintenance division have voted to strike for one day next Monday and to
withdraw 24 hour on-call cover indefinitely from 18 January.
The staff - members of the NUCPS civil service union - voted by 83 per cent
to 17 per cent to back industrial disruption in a postal ballot with a 65
per cent turnout.
The staff are concerned at the government's refusal to provide redundancy
and severance protection when the service is privatised. The union's general
secretary, Mr John Sheldon, said: 'I find it incredible the Treasury is
willing to jeopardise such a key service. All we are asking for is fair
treatment. The government have given guarantees to staff in other privatised
departments - why are we different?'
The Home Office said the government was still discussing terms and
conditions for staff in the proposed privatisation. Any new owner would have
to meet legal obligations to existing staff.
The union said staff feared a repetition of a situation last year where the
Astra company, which acquired Skillcentres, collapsed into receivership with
hundreds of staff being made redundant on minimum terms rather than those
covering the civil service.
</TEXT>
