<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / Free vote on capital punishment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is to allow MPs a free vote on capital punishment as part of
its drive against crime, it was announced last night.
Mr David Maclean, home office minister of state, said the vote would be the
only opportunity for MPs to express a view on hanging in the current
parliament, which must end by 1997.
The vote will form part of the debate on the criminal justice bill, which
the government claims will give the UK the most comprehensive framework
possible for fighting crime.
Mr Maclean also confirmed that MPs will be given a free vote on proposals to
reduce the age of consent for homosexuals from 21.
The last Commons vote on capital punishment was in December 1990, when a
Conservative backbench attempt to impose the death penalty for the murder of
a police officer was rejected by 350 votes to 215. Conservative supporters
of the death penalty believe capital punishment is unlikely to be
reinstated.
Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, said the bill - the cornerstone of
the troubled 'back to basics' programme - would implement 18 of the 27
law-and-order initiatives launched at last year's Tory party conference.
Mr Howard said these initiatives rested on 'basic, commonsense principles'
which would make life 'safer for the law-abiding and more difficult for the
criminal'.
The bill was given an unopposed second reading after MPs rejected by 319
votes to 275 a Labour amendment calling for stronger crime prevention
measures and an independent review authority to monitor miscarriages of
justice.
Mr Tony Blair, shadow home secretary, said the bill's purpose was to provide
balance and strategy to a government that lacked both.
'What people want after 14 years is not another dose of Tory rhetoric but
effective actions that work,' he said.
Mr Blair appeared to surprise Mr Howard by revealing that Labour would
abstain in the second-reading vote if its own amendment was rejected.
Mr Howard argued that Labour's stance showed it could not make up its mind
on the wide range of proposals covered by the bill. When Mr Blair 'sits on
his hands tonight, the British public will see that his rhetoric is just hot
air,' the home secretary said.
Mr Howard attempted to defuse criticism of the failure to include moves to
set up an independent review authority by pledging 'shortly' to publish a
consultation paper on the subject.
The home secretary emphasised that he accepted a recent Royal Commission
recommendation that such a body be established and was 'determined' to
ensure that effective machinery was set up.
But he said a number of issues, including the relationship between the new
authority and both ministers and the Court of Appeal, had still to be
resolved. These matters were being taken forward urgently.
</TEXT>
