<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / Backbenchers wonder who will be next: 'Back to basics'
debacle is 'a little flurry', says PM - Criminal justice bill is outlined
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The prime minister may have dismissed the controversy over his 'back to
basics' policy as 'a little flurry', but in the Commons tea rooms and bars
backbenchers could talk of little else.
As MPs returned to Westminster after the Christmas recess, many were
wondering who was going to be the next victim of the scandals that have
slammed the brakes on the careers of Mr Tim Yeo, the former environment
minister and Mr Alan Duncan, the former parliamentary private secretary to
health minister Dr Brian Mawhinney.
A throughly fed-up parliamentary private secretary said it was now
impossible for MPs to be seen out alone with anyone apart from their wives.
'It's now got to the stage that there could be rumours about my sexuality if
I dine out with a male friend. That is not what 'back to basics' was meant
to be about,' he said angrily.
In the fraught atmosphere, a Scottish Conservative backbencher believed he
may have narrowly escaped becoming the lastest casualty when he was
photographed by a journalist leaving a lunchtime function with a woman half
his age. She was his research assistant.
A senior Tory backbencher, a close friend of the MP, said the story
illustrated how 'back to basics' was in danger of being engulfed in personal
scandals. 'If the media go to that length to catch MPs out, then of course
they will find politicians who have erred and we will all look ridiculous.'
Tory MPs' views mosly fall into three categories:
The moralising tendency. This was best illustrated by Mr David Shaw, the
rightwing MP for Dover, who said he was not in favour of witch hunts but
warned ministers to examine their consciences before speaking out on 'back
to basics'.
Mr Shaw, who has attended Republican conventions in the US where the moral
majority has held sway for more than a decade, believes MPs cannot divorce
morality from politics.
'Many businessmen,' he said, 'would not employ people of low moral
standards, employees who womanise or who drink too much. Why should
politicians be any different?'
A former trade minister, Mr Edward Leigh, appeared to go further in urging
the government to 'attack the permissive society funded by the state'. He
said there had to be a moral dimension and ministers should 'stick with it'
in spite of the uproar over errant MPs' behaviour. The frightened tendency.
A nervous backbencher, whose eyes kept darting across the members' lobby as
MPs left the chamber following prime ministers questions, urged the
government to 'put a lid on this awful pandora's box'.
He said the moralising of some cabinet members had given the tabloids the
justification they were looking for to report on private lives. 'Where will
it stop?' he asked, concerned that reporters are asking too many
embarrassing personal questions.
The 'prime minister is to blame' tendency. 'The policy is fine' said one
querulous minister, 'the prime minister's handling of it is not.' He thought
that Mr Major should not have let cabinet members interpret the policy in
different ways.
Another parliamentary private secretary gave a sigh when asked what had gone
wrong. 'If only John Major had the bottle to sack Tim Yeo when it was known
he had fathered a child outside marriage we may not have got into this
terrible mess.'
Some MPs believe the government will survive the crisis as long as there are
no more revelations. Others predict the scandal will continue to run unless
the policy is redefined.
It was left to Mr Leigh to sum up the mood of the pessimists when he
predicted the government would get itself together only to stumble into
another crisis.
</TEXT>
