<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / Corrupt plot over Sizewell admitted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A former procurement manager with NEI Thompson Kennicott, the engineering
company taken over by Rolls-Royce in 1989, yester-day pleaded guilty at
Southwark Crown Court in London to a charge of conspiracy to corrupt, John
Mason writes.
Mr Robert Wilcox, of Colchester, Essex, admitted conspiring to receive gifts
in connection with contracts awarded to NEI by the Central Electricity
Generating Board for its Sizewell B power station.
Two other men, Mr Donald Richards, the head of Donnar Services, a marketing
company, and Mr Colin Read, another former NEI project manager, in September
admitted a similar offence of corruption. All three have been released on
bail and will be sentenced later.
Mr Wilcox's guilty plea ends a series of prosecutions by the Serious Fraud
Office over cases of corruption in tenders for big projects. The previous
investigations centred on contracts awarded by BP and Shell in their North
Sea oil operations and Transmarche Link for the Channel tunnel.
