<PROFILE>_AN-EALDDAB3FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940112
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / Company gains land use reprieve
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An award-winning company which faced enforcement action to prevent it using
former Ministry of Defence buildings on green belt land for storage was
yesterday given a reprieve.
Mayflower Glass, a manufacturer of decorative glassware which won the
Queen's Award for Export in 1992 and 1993, had been threatened with
enforcement action by South Tyneside council but now has another six months
to resolve its planning problems.
Last Friday the company laid off 50 employees, half its workforce, because
the planning dispute forced it to reduce stocks.
The MoD did not need planning consent because its depot buildings were Crown
property. The company bought them in 1985 from the Property Services Agency
but has been unable to obtain planning permission.
Mr Harry Phipps, chairman and founder, said Mayflower had to have storage
space near its factory, which was located just outside the green belt,
because it had to transport very delicate, part-manufactured products to and
from its warehouse.
He said the planning issue had not been considered a problem when the
company bought the buildings.
After three six-month extensions, the last of which expired on December 31,
the council threatened an enforcement notice. But, after a three-hour
meeting with the company yesterday, it said it would work to help resolve
the problem.
Mr Phipps said the 50 laid-off employees would be asked to return to work
today.
</TEXT>
