<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / Cavallo to end his attacks on Brazil
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BARHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUENOS AIRES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
To the relief of the Brazilian government, Mr Domingo Cavallo, Argentina's
economy minister, has promised to end his scathing attacks on Brazil's
economic policies. Mr Cavallo yesterday said: 'I will not comment any more
about Brazil. I will not answer any more questions about Brazil.'
Mr Cavallo, who in three years transformed Argentina's chaotic and
hyper-inflationary economy, has made a habit of publicly criticising
Brazil's economic policies. He often says these are based on 'hunger' and
'impoverishment of the people'.
Although the Brazilian government has never protested formally, it has made
its displeasure known to Mr Cavallo.
A Brazilian official said yesterday 'we are not going to say anything
because this should have been his attitude right from the start. These
statements harm our relations.'
However, Mr Cavallo, is credited with helping convince Mr Fernando Henrique
Cardoso, Brazil's finance minister, to propose orthodox policies similar to
Argentina's.
