<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / Maxwell liquidators recover Pounds 27m from Lehman
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pension schemes formerly controlled by the late Mr Robert Maxwell, were
boosted by a further Pounds 27m when Lehman Brothers, the US-based
investment bank, yesterday returned disputed shares - the second such refund
of contested securities within the past week.
Last week, Bank of America agreed to return Pounds 25m to the Mirror Group
Newspapers Pension Scheme, settling a claim which had been the subject of a
writ.
The Lehman holdings, units in a Lazard Property Unit Trust and shares in the
Daily Telegraph, were part of a Pounds 100m writ filed against Lehman
Brothers last September by Robson Rhodes, liquidator of the
Maxwell-controlled fund manager, Bishopsgate Investment Management.
Lehman Brothers said it intended to defend its claim to the remaining Pounds
73m. However, it said it continued 'to support initiatives designed to
achieve an early resolution of the disputes surrounding the collapse of the
Maxwell empire'.
The shares were actually returned last November, but Lehman Brothers and
Robson Rhodes delayed announcing the development while both parties
discussed a possible settlement of the entire claim.
The refund was made after Robson Rhodes informed Lehman Brothers it would
seek a so-called summary judgment in respect of that portion of its writ.
'Our claim to these shares was so good it was not even a triable issue,'
said Mr Neil Cooper, partner at Robson Rhodes. Among other things, the
Lazard Property Unit Trust could only be owned by a tax-exempt entity such
as a pension scheme and Lehman Brothers could not legally have taken title
to them, the writ alleged.
Robson Rhodes has been seeking return of the securities from Lehman Brothers
since December 1991, and has in the past accused Lehman Brothers of trying
to obstruct its efforts to trace assets claimed by pensioners.
Yesterday, Lehman Brothers said: 'Having satisfied ourselves of the facts of
the claim and that the securities belong to the Common Investment Fund (of
the Maxwell pension schemes) and not to any other party, we were very
pleased to make this move.'
Meanwhile, Sir Peter Webster, appointed as a government mediator to seek a
'global solution' to the myriad claims by the pension schemes against banks,
insurance companies and advisers, is said to be making progress.
Mr Frank Field, chairman of the Parliamentary Select Committee on Social
Security, which has held extensive hearings on the Maxwell pension scandal,
said the recent refunds to the schemes are a good sign.
</TEXT>
