<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / Dublin to lift TV ban on Sinn Fein
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Irish government is to lift its broadcasting ban on Sinn Fein from
January 19, when the present banning order expires, allowing leaders of the
political wing of the IRA to be interviewed on Irish TV and radio for the
first time in almost two decades.
Downing Street responded coolly to yesterday's move, saying it 'noted' the
decision, which was a matter entirely for the Irish government. It said a
review of Britain's broadcasting ban would not be completed for 'some
weeks'.
Explaining Dublin's decision, Mr Michael D. Higgins, minister for
broadcasting, called the ban 'an appallingly blunt instrument . . . which
removed broadcasters' discretion and authority'.
He said the onus would now be on the independent broadcasting authorities to
prevent views being aired which would incite crime or violence, and which
could be sanctioned under other provisions of the Republic's broadcasting
legislation or criminal legislation.
'The Irish people abhor violence and those who support violence should be
submitted to critical questioning like everyone else. Cloaking them is
against the public interest,' Mr Higgins said.
The minister said that a review of the ban had been under way for more than
a year, before the present Anglo-Irish peace initiative. He said the lifting
of the ban was made for 'broadcasting reasons and not as some kind of sop to
Sinn Fein', although he said current efforts to persuade the IRA to abandon
violence and bring Sinn Fein to the negotiating table provided 'a very
important context' to the decision.
'The atmosphere is very different to when the ban was first introduced (in
1976),' he said.
Mr Joe Mulholland, director of news for the state TV and radio station RTE,
said the decision was 'a step forward'. Mr Gerry Adams, the president of
Sinn Fein, also welcomed the decision, saying it 'was long overdue'.
Labour welcomed the move and said the British ban should be lifted 'as soon
as possible without prejudice to the recent Anglo-Irish declaration'. But Ms
Mo Mowlam, shadow heritage secretary, said she was 'reticent to call for it
to be lifted today'.
Mr Michael Mates, former Northern Ireland minister, said he hoped the
British ban would not be lifted 'unless and until' the IRA ended its armed
campaign. Three policemen were injured in a bomb attack on their Land Rover
in east Belfast last night.
</TEXT>
