<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / Pound hits six-month high against the D-Mark
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sterling touched its highest level for six months against the D-Mark
yesterday as the German currency weakened and investors bought pounds in the
expectation that the UK will decide against an early cut in interest rates.
Ahead of today's monthly monetary meeting between Mr Kenneth Clarke, the
chancellor, and Mr Eddie George, the governor of the Bank of England, the
pound rose to DM2.5981 in London and threatened to break through the key
market barrier of DM2.60. In New York it closed at DM2.5925.
While growing evidence of a strengthening consumer-led recovery and fears of
increased factory prices have damped expectations of an early interest rate
cut, some foreign exchange dealers reason that the UK will have to act if
the pound strengthens much beyond DM2.60.
The pound later slipped in London to DM2.5944, up from Monday's close of
DM2.5883. Against the dollar it eased to Dollars 1.4913 from Dollars 1.4955.
But its recent strong performance prompted some exchange dealers to
speculate that lower interest rates are still on the UK policy agenda.
Currencies, Page 35
</TEXT>
