<DATE>940111
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Clinton warns of threat to credibility
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER and DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US president Bill Clinton warned European allies yesterday that the North
Atlantic Treaty Organisation must be ready to carry out threats of military
action in Bosnia or risk the credibility of the alliance.
'If the situation does not improve, the alliance must be prepared to act,'
he said on the opening day of the Nato summit. However, he later made clear
there was no question of an immediate decision to launch air strikes.
He told other Nato leaders that threats of action 'cannot be seen as mere
rhetoric'. Those who attacked Sarajevo, the Bosnian capital, must understand
that Nato was serious, he said.
Arguments over Bosnia threatened to undermine the image of renewed purpose
which Nato sought to project at the summit, primarily through the forging of
new links with former enemies in central and eastern Europe. Mr Clinton said
at a press conference that Nato's opening to the east, less than three years
after the disbandment of the Warsaw pact, was the real issue of the day.
The 16 leaders yesterday launched their Partnership for Peace project
inviting former Warsaw pact countries, including Russia and the rest of the
former Soviet Union, to negotiate military ties.
The plan is a compromise which holds out the prospect of eventual membership
for some former communist countries while acknowledging the opposition of
Russian hardliners who fear encirclement by Nato. Poland's president Lech
Walesa said the plan was 'a step that is too short but in the right
direction.' The alliance hopes eastern European partners will join in
taskforces for regional conflicts. The summit is also due to approve a new
command structure designed to help Nato deal more effectively with crises
such as Bosnia.
Last night allied leaders met for discussions in depth on Bosnia and the
possible use of air-strikes to halt the fighting between Serbs, Croats and
Moslems and ensure that UN troops carry out relief missions. But even before
the evening talks, divisions resurfaced among allies. Britain and Canada
expressed reservations about the risks of military action, including
possible reprisals against their troops serving with the UN.
Mr Andre Ouellet, Canadian foreign minister, told reporters: 'An air strike
might solve a minor circumstantial problem but could create a number of
other difficulties and make our troops be perceived as belligerents.'
Mr Douglas Hurd, UK foreign minister, said the threat of air strikes - which
was first made last year - 'might well be implemented'. But he warned that
any action would have to be carefully considered.
British officials have tried to avoid making the Bosnian conflict a
benchmark for Nato's credibility, but Mr Clinton's declaration was explicit.
'What is at stake is not just the safety of the people in Sarajevo and any
possibility of bringing this terrible conflict to an end, but the
credibility of the alliance itself,' he said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BAZ  Bosnia-Hercegovina, East Europe.
    FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
