<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity Futures and Options Trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An erratic and less confident performance from derivatives markets took its
toll of equities again yesterday, writes Terry Byland.
The March contract on the FT-SE 100 Index undermined the stock market at
first, when it failed to hold a premium of 15 to 20 points against cash, and
caused share prices to hurriedly abandon early gains.
The contract continued to drift down for much of the remainder of the
session, before rallying as Wall Steet opened in good form. At the day's
worst, the March contract was at a discount of several points against its
fair value premium, currently estimated at 13 points, unchanged from last
week. But by the close, a premium of 9 points to fair value had been
restored. Volume slipped below last week's levels to record 12,635 bargains.
Dealers pointed out that there had been no opportunity for the arbitrage
operations between futures and underlying stocks which enlivened both
markets last week. Yesterday, the locals, or independent traders, found
themselves left to trade amongst themselves. The big securities houses were
content to tidy up any outstanding trading situations positions but
uninterested in opening up new ones.
Business in traded options was reduced, the final total of 33,868 contracts
contrasting with nearly 55,000 on Friday. Volume in the Footsie contract
dipped to 9,136 from 13,717, while the Euro FT-SE contract returned 3,314.
Among individual contracts, Ladbroke, the leisure, bookmaking and hotels
group, topped the list with 3,297 as investors continued to reasses the
implications of the departure of the chairman.
</TEXT>
