<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / London Stock Exchange: Share prices end erratic session with
a rally - Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A highly volatile, but finally unconvincing, session in London stocks saw
share prices consolidating around existing levels rather than developing any
new trends. Non-Footsie stocks again attracted significant interest
although, here again, the focus was on con-solidation.
Traders expressed concern over the volatility which has featured equities
since Christmas. Stock index futures led share prices yesterday but there
was no sign of specific pressures in the derivatives markets. Hopes for base
rate cuts appeared to have been put back to spring once more, and weakness
in government bonds took the bounce out of the stock market.
A strong start to the new Wall Street session gave a closing boost to a
London market which had moved through a near 40-point Footsie range earlier
in the day. Marketmakers were still struggling to attract stocks to
replenish their trading books.
At its final reading the FT-SE 100 Index was down 5.4 at 3,440.6. London
opened well, hoping for a continuation of Friday's advance, but was
undermined when the stock index futures refused to support the initial
optimism.
A gain of 22 Footsie points in pre-trading was quickly wiped off within a
few minutes of the opening of the derivatives markets. Shares then drifted
down and the Footsie showed a loss of 16 points as it waited for Wall Street
to open. The rally in London came slowly, as the Dow Industrial Average
gained 15 points in UK trading hours.
The FT-SE Mid 250 Index also gave ground, slipping 11.1 to 3,901.4. But
trading in non-Footsie stocks made up around 66 per cent of the day's Seaq
total of 849.1m shares, well above daily averages.
Stock exchange statistics disclosed that Friday's Seaq volume of 1.4bn
shares was worth Pounds 2.25bn in retail business, nearly twice the daily
average for last year. This bore out suggestions that the big institutions
have been busy reshaping their portfolios, often moving out of selected blue
chips and into second line issues. In an unusual development, last week saw
the FT-SE Mid 250 Index setting the pace for the blue chip sectors.
This has in part been prompted by the powerful influence exerted on the
Footsie stocks from the derivatives market, which has given rise to some
concern over the valuations put on the Footsie list by the pre-Christmas
boom.
The market was held back by the less buoyant mood in oil shares, as well as
by caution among some domestic sectors as they awaited the January round of
profits statements.
Uncertainty still hung over the retail sector as it looked for definitive
news from the Christmas sales. However, some analysts believe that any
weakness in retail sales might benefit the stock market by prompting the cut
in base rates on which a further advance in share prices appears to depend.
Some other consumer sectors ran into profit-takers and the banks, which
outperformed strongly in December, were mostly easier ahead of their trading
statements - the exception being TSB which opens the season later this week.
London's ready response to Wall Street was seen as a promising indication of
underlying confidence. Hopes that interest rates can remain low in the US
revived last week, contrasting with the bout of nervousness over the US
economy suffered in the previous week.
</TEXT>
