<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow climbs strongly to new
record
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
After a hesitant start, US share prices rocketed further into record
territory yesterday amid strong demand for cyclical stocks, writes Patrick
Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average scored yet another all-time high, finishing
44.74 stronger at 3,865.51. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500
also ended at a new record peak, adding 5.37 at 475.27, although the
American SE composite finished 0.71 off at 478.78. The Nasdaq composite
gained 3.75 at 786.69. New York SE trading volume totalled 319.5m shares.
Although the market stuttered at the opening bell, sending prices lower in
the first hour, the buying that pushed the leading indices to record highs
last week quickly materialised again.
By mid-morning the Dow and the S&amp;P were in positive territory, with demand
concentrated mostly on stocks sensitive to the economic cycle. Analysts
again attributed the buying, which picked up strongly in the afternoon, to
institutions putting to work the cash they received from investors in the
new year.
The money flows were sufficiently strong to offset yesterday's decline in
bond prices, which pushed long-term interest rates up to 6.23 per cent.
Among individual issues, automotive stocks were particularly strong as
investors anticipated continued demand for cars and trucks.
Chrysler appreciated Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 58 3/4 , Ford Motor put on
Dollars 2 3/4 at Dollars 67 1/4 and General Motors, aided by an analyst's
upgrade, added Dollars 1 3/8 at Dollars 59 1/4 . Other cyclicals that were
firmer included United Technologies, up Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 64,
International Paper, Dollars 1 ahead at Dollars 73 5/8 , and Alcoa, Dollars
1 7/8 higher at Dollars 74 1/8 .
The latest development in the bid battle for Paramount Communications - last
Friday's announced merger between Blockbuster and Viacom and their new,
revised offer for Paramount - left investors unimpressed.
Paramount fell Dollars 2 to Dollars 77 1/4 , Viacom 'B' shares dropped
Dollars 3 to Dollars 38, Blockbuster eased Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 28 and
QVC Network, which still has the highest bid on the table, shed Dollars 1
3/8 to Dollars 39 1/4 .
Canada
After Friday's pause, Toronto share prices resumed their recent advance with
a solid gain that moved the TSE 300 index to a record high, helped by a
strong bond market.
The Bank of Canada's key lending rate is expected to fall five to seven
basis points at its weekly setting today to below 4 per cent for the first
time since summer 1963.
The index ended 32.5 ahead at 4,453.2, while rises outnumbered declines by
459 to 354. Further heavy volume of 71.4m shares was recorded. The financial
services group led the way with a rise of 1.78 per cent.
</TEXT>
