<PROFILE>_AN-EAKC0AFZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940111
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Survey of West Bengal (1): Climate changes for industry -
The Marxist government is wooing foreign investment amid clear signs of
industrial revival in the state
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SHIRAZ SIDHVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A sense of quiet optimism pervades West Bengal's business community. After a
quarter of a century of decline, the state's industrial revival seems very
much on the cards. In Calcutta, the eastern seaport which is the natural
gateway to emerging Asian nations, there is a strong campaign to revive some
of the region's lost glory as India's prime industrial heartland.
Two and a half years ago, when the Indian government embarked on its
economic reforms programme, it seemed unlikely that West Bengal, plagued by
power cuts, dead telephone lines and a declining economy, could compete with
other states to benefit from the opening up of India's economy. Today,
industry leaders are confident that West Bengal, with its strategic
location, skilled manpower and wealth of natural resources, will recreate
the industrial climate that was allowed to wither in the late 1960s.
There is reason for the optimism. After a period of stagnation, when
virtually no new investment was made in the state, over 258 projects
involving foreign investment of Rs55.9bn had been cleared by the government
up to September 1993. The Marxist state government is actively wooing
foreign investment.
There has been a dramatic improvement in power supplies - West Bengal
already has a surplus, and new power projects are being commissioned.
Telecommunications have been modernised, and telephones actually work. Last
month, businessmen, who were forced to travel to Delhi or Bombay for
international flight connections, rejoiced when British Airways and KLM
resumed operations to Calcutta.
The first signs of an industrial revival came in 1990, with the country's
two largest private sector groups - the Tatas and Reliance Industries -
investing Rs30bn and Rs3.9bn respectively in a new petrochemicals complex at
Haldia and a plastics factory. The Reliance project has yet to materialise,
but the interest shown by the two big houses was enough to put Calcutta
firmly back on the country's industrial map. The government has claimed that
the setting up of a new industrial belt at Haldia, south of Calcutta, could
create 150,000 jobs, but work on the Haldia project has been slow in
starting.
Other large projects include a Rs7.5bn pig iron plant proposed by the
Birlas, a leading Calcutta business group, Tata Iron and Steel's pig iron
plant which is nearing completion in Kharagpur, and telecom- munications and
electronic projects by Siemens and Philips respectively.
According to the Bengal Chamber of Commerce, industrial investment in West
Bengal, which averaged 9 per cent growth a year until the mid-1960s, was
falling by 0.5 per cent a year by 1985. The resource-rich region once
accounted for over 80 per cent of the country's industry but its virtual
monopoly did not survive Independence. Other parts of the country were not
obliged to deal with the problems of over-manning which new technology
exposed in West Bengal's industries.
Management controls deteriorated and several companies closed when British
and other overseas-owned companies were forced to reduce their stakes by the
socialist government in Delhi. The political instability brought about by
the ultra-left Naxalite movement in the late 1960s accentuated the problem
for a while. West Bengal's decline had begun and little was done to arrest
the damage for over 25 years, 16 of them under Marxist rule.
'The flight of top management, more than the flight of capital, contributed
to Calcutta's slide,' says Mr Mumtaz Ahmad, past president of the Bengal
Chamber. Companies such as Bata, Britannia Biscuits, Brooke Bond and Lipton
moved away from Calcutta. Even though ITC, an associate of BAT Industries,
stayed, it invested in other Indian states.
Meanwhile, the national government exercised strict control over new
investments so that it could often influence business houses to set up in
the part of the country it favoured. 'All that has changed now,' says Mr
Ahmad. 'In terms of infrastructure, natural resources like coal, plentiful
water and power, and the disciplined attitude of labour, we are all set to
compete, industry-wise and state-wise.
'The new investor to India will take the path of least resistance, and the
state government has now realised that unless we woo him, he will go
elsewhere,' says Mr Ahmad, a member of a West Bengal government committee on
infrastructure improvement, who was largely responsible for British Airways'
return to Calcutta. 'India was opening up, and Mr Basu's government realised
that if it didn't fall into line, it would be left behind.'
Indeed, the Communist Party of India (Marxist) government with Mr Jyoti Basu
at the helm, sees no contradiction between its traditional ideology and the
encouragement of a free market economy. He once explained the reason for
'the change of climate' in the state, saying: 'We criticised capitalism, but
the capitalism we criticised, no longer exists. Capitalism has changed, and
we have to change.'
Addressing potential investors in London in September last year, Mr Basu
admitted that his government had turned its immediate attention to
agriculture 'with a special emphasis on land reform for restructuring
retrograde agrarian relations.'
The West Bengal government has established a successful local
self-government system, or 'panchayats' at the village level, to allow
peasants exploited by feudal land acts to enhance their dignity, and thus
their productivity. Almost 50 per cent of the state's plan allocation has
been channelled to this decentralisation process, and as a result food
output is growing at about 5 per cent a year, one of the highest rates in
India.
Better living conditions in the villages have reduced migration to the
cities, though the influx from neighbouring states Bihar and Orissa, and
from Bangladesh have put a strain on West Bengal's already overstretched
urban resources.
Mr Basu believes that agriculture can now serve as a springboard for
industry in the state. The chief minister, who many people say is
single-handedly steering reform in the state, is keen to develop food
processing to augment traditional agro-based industries such as tea and
jute.
The development of an electronics industry could, in turn, complement the
traditional steel and engineering industries. The potential of export-led,
labour-intensive industries has appealed to Mr Basu, who is hard-pressed to
solve the state's high unemployment. The example of neighbouring Bangladesh
as a leading garment exporter is tempting to follow: the chief minister once
remarked that Calcutta had a lot of tailors, but virtually no garment
industry.
For the new investor, West Bengal has very real advantages over other Indian
regions. The state is rich in mineral wealth - coal, graphite, china clay,
granite and other precious minerals. It has a highly diversified
agricultural base, and its climate and soil are perfect for horticulture.
Technical personnel and skilled manpower are easily available, and the
financial services and banking sectors are well-developed.
But many disadvantages have still to be surmounted: an inadequate seaport, a
capital city bursting at the seams and virtually no development of satellite
townships around Calcutta, or any infrastructure to talk of in the state's
hinterland. At Writers Building, the state's seat of power, bureaucracy is
rife, with most ministers sitting on mountains of unattended paperwork.
'Change takes time to permeate,' says Mr Pradeep Das Gupta, secretary of the
Bengal Chamber. 'The government has been late in announcing a new industrial
development policy, and the sooner this is done, the better. But it is clear
that the government means business, and is thinking of an aggressive
marketing approach to sell West Bengal to foreign investors.'
Mr Krishan Lal Chugh, chairman of ITC, one of the few multinational
companies with roots firmly entrenched in Calcutta, believes the
'much-maligned city' can become a showpiece for the rest of India. He points
out that 'power cuts have been banished to Delhi,' and that Calcutta, with
its reasonable rents and stylish clubs is 'the cheapest Indian city for
executives to live in today.' The labour climate has improved, and the
quality of skilled workers and management-level executives is still the best
in the country. 'Bengal should sell,' says Mr Chugh resolutely.
</TEXT>
