<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Government Bonds: Jitters over new supply leave long-dated
gilt prices lower
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Auction jitters pushed UK government bond prices lower yesterday and,
although the market recovered slightly, long-dated gilts still ended the day
about a quarter of a point lower.
Dealers expect the Bank of England to announce the preliminary details of
the January gilt auction this week. The market expects the new supply to be
at the very long end, with either a new 20-year or a new 25-year gilt as the
auction stock.
Such an announcement is likely to depress long-dated gilts, dealers said,
especially since it would probably be interpreted as signalling that the
Bank sees little scope for a further reduction in long gilt yields.
The economic news released yesterday had little impact on gilt prices and
economists said it provided confirmation of a recovery, although the
consumer credit figures were slightly weaker than expected, with net
consumer credit rising by Pounds 290m in November.
Looking ahead this week, the gilt market will focus on the unemployment
figures tomorrow and the meeting between the Mr Kenneth Clark, the
chancellor of the exchequer and Mr Eddie George, the governor of the Bank of
England, for a signal on interest rates.
Among the high-yielding European government bond markets Italy closed
three-quarters of a point down, rattled by further political scandals,
dealers said.
The Liffe March futures contract ended 0.78 down at 117.10, off the low
price of 117.05. The bond market fell on rumours that top politicians were
involved in an alleged attempt to hush up a scandal over secret service
slush funds.
Spanish bonds saw some weakness, dealers reporting foreign selling of
Spanish paper because of worries about the peseta and unease over the
Banesto debacle.
German government bonds ended the day almost unchanged, showing little
response to news that western Germany's gross domestic product shrunk by 1.9
per cent in 1993, following growth of 1.6 per cent in 1992.
Elsewhere in Europe, the French market fell back on disappointment over the
lack of an interest rate cut.
Swedish government bonds, which had rallied strongly last week as details of
the government's budget proposals leaked into the market, ended yesterday
little changed as expectations were generally confirmed, dealers said.
After early profit-taking following last Friday's strong rally had pushed US
Treasury prices lower in the morning, the bond market rallied in the
afternoon to leave longer-dated issues little changed.
In late trading, the benchmark 30-year government bond was down only 3/32 at
100 1/4 , yielding 6.226 per cent, and the two-year note unchanged at 100
11/32 , to yield 4.049 per cent.
The selling of longer-dated Treasuries began overnight on foreign markets
and, after a brief rebound, continued into the morning in New York. Traders
were not concerned by the activity, which they categorised as natural
profit-taking.
</TEXT>
