<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / International Company News: Michelin to launch FFr3.5bn
convertible bond
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Michelin, the French tyre manufacturer, yesterday announced it would launch
a FFr3.5bn convertible bond issue in a move to reduce its debt, diversify
its sources of finance and reinforce its financial structure.
The company, which had first-half losses of FFr3.19bn (Dollars 540m) last
year after provisions for restructuring, has debts of about FFr30bn.
Michelin said last night, however, that it was confident of recovery in the
international tyre market. It said the recovery in the North American market
should continue over the next few years and that the sharp price competition
which started at the beginning of last year had stabilised.
In Europe, which suffered a particularly sharp contraction in 1993, Michelin
said there were signs that the decline in sales had ended. Some markets,
such as the UK, had seen the start of recovery, according to the company.
The group said its restructuring plan, which involves the loss of 2,950 jobs
and a reduction of operating costs by FFr3.5bn by the middle of next year,
was on schedule. Provisions for the costs of the restructuring plan, which
total about FFr2.6bn, were taken in the first half of last year.
Industry analysts in Paris said that the convertible bond issue was timed to
tap the buoyant Paris stock market. Yesterday, the CAC-40 index of leading
shares reached another record, rising 0.4 per cent to close at 2,317.
Under the terms of the issue, to be launched on January 12, bonds will be
priced at FFr255. On Monday, before news of the issue, Michelin shares rose
FFr3 to a 12-month high of FFr229.1.
The bonds, which can be exchanged on the basis of one for one share from
February 2, will mature on January 1, 2001. They will carry an interest rate
of 2.5 per cent, or FFr6.38, payable on January 1 each year.
Michelin said the yield would be 5.03 per cent if the bonds are not
converted. On maturity, they will be repaid at FFr307 each, or 120.39 per
cent of the issue price.
Existing shareholders will be given a priority entitlement of one bond for
every 15 shares between January 12 and January 21 inclusive.
</TEXT>
