<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / International Company News: Gillette shake-up costs Dollars
164m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Gillette, the US shaving and consumer products group, yesterday announced
plans to reorganise its overseas operations in a move that will bring 2,000
job losses over the next two years and a one-time after-tax charge of
Dollars 164m in the fourth quarter of 1993.
It said sales, profits and earnings were expected to reach record levels in
the fourth quarter before special charges, reflecting the introduction of
new products and the inclusion for the first time of results from Parker
Pen, which it bought last May.
The company said that the job losses, which represent about 6 per cent of
the workforce, would fall largely outside the US, but did not specify where.
Gillette said that the cuts were likely to be balanced by growth elsewhere,
so overall employment would remain roughly at the present level of 34,000 by
the end of the year.
Mr Alfred Zeien, chairman and chief executive, said the company needed to
reorganise so that it could compete more effectively and expand in
international markets.
