<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / International Company News: Euro Disney banks may seek theme
park shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Euro Disney banks may demand changes in the management and operation of
the EuroDisneyland theme park as part of the emergency financial
restructuring package for the troubled leisure group.
The banks are awaiting a review of Euro Disney that they commissioned last
month from the Paris office of KPMG Peat Marwick, the accountancy and
consulting group. Euro Disney, which lost FFr5.3bn (Dollars 898m) in the
year to September 30, is threatened by bankruptcy unless the banks agree to
a rescue package.
KPMG has been asked to audit Euro Disney's financial position and its
capital requirements. The preliminary version of this report, which will
form the basis of the banks' strategy in the restructuring talks with Euro
Disney and Walt Disney, its US parent company, is scheduled for completion
by the end of this week.
The banks have charged KPMG with analysing Euro Disney's business plan so
that the banks can decide whether changes will be required in the running of
the park and in its cost base. This report, which is expected to take longer
to finish than the financial audit, will be used to assess whether the banks
should ask for strategic or personnel changes to be made at Euro Disney.
'There is deep dissatisfaction among the banks as to the way that Disney has
managed Euro Disney,' said a banker involved with the negotiations. 'It is
possible that we may press for changes. We also have to be sure that the
cost base comes down. But nothing will be decided until KPMG has completed
its work.'
Walt Disney would be expected to resist any attempt by the banks to
influence the running of Euro Disney. It prides itself on its strong
corporate culture and was, until the Euro Disney debacle, regarded as one of
the most most successful companies in the US.
However the banks, which have been asked by Disney to exchange part of their
FFr20.3bn loans for equity as part of the restructuring package, are anxious
to protect their position.
Disney has implemented changes at Euro Disney since the park's opening in
April 1992. Many of the original US executives have been replaced by
Europeans. Mr Philippe Bourguignon, chairman, has overhauled Euro Disney's
policies for marketing, merchandising and pricing.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Euro Disney.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
