<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / UK Company News: Hewlett-Packard UK at Pounds 83m -
Worldwide profits performance more than doubles to Dollars 1.2bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK subsidiary of Hewlett-Packard, the US-based computers and electronics
group, outperformed its parent last year with a Pounds 90m turnround in
pre-tax profits and a 43 per cent increase in turnover to more than Pounds
1bn.
Worldwide, HP reported profits of Dollars 1.2bn (Pounds 810m) in 1993, up
from Dollars 549m the previous year. Revenues rose 23 per cent to Dollars
20.3bn, making it the second largest computer manufacturer in the US and
easily the most profitable.
The UK subsidiary made a pre-tax profit of Pounds 82.6m compared with a
Pounds 7.4m loss the previous year. Mr John Golding, UK managing director,
played down the profit improvement pointing out that the figures reflected
internal accounting policy rather than trading performance.
He attached more importance to the growth in overall turnover, which reached
Pounds 1.02bn, and to a 50 per cent increase in exports to Pounds 324m.
Mr Golding said the company's performance was the result of quality
programmes, eliminating waste, consolidating operations and keeping expenses
under control.
During the year, HP bought Colorado Memory Systems (Europe) and BT&amp;D
Technologies, strengthening its activities in computer mass storage and in
telecommunications.
HP seems to have proved itself better able to ride out the recession and
turbulence in the global computer industry than other large computer
manufacturers.
It is, according to Mr Golding, profitable in all its product sectors
including computer systems, printers, calculators and electronic
instruments. It is strengthening its performance in personal computers and
is now the fourth largest pc vendor in Europe.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Hewlett-Packard Co Inc.
</CO>
