<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / RHM helps Tomkins double profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tomkins, the industrial group, nearly doubled interim pre-tax profits, from
Pounds 47.1m to Pounds 93.8m, with the help of Ranks Hovis McDougall, the
food group acquired for Pounds 990.5m in December 1992.
Mr Greg Hutchings, chief executive, said the rise in profits was achieved in
spite of difficult trading conditions, with few signs of recovery in Europe.
At the operating level, RHM contributed profits of Pounds 38.5m to a total
of Pounds 85.9m, with milling and baking making Pounds 7.1m of that. Concern
over intense competition in the baking industry has led Tomkins' shares to
underperform since the acquisition.
Mr Hutchings was upbeat yesterday about prospects, but the shares fell 3p to
259p. Since acquiring RHM, 22 facilities had been closed and 2,860
redundancies made, cutting the workforce by 11 per cent.
Tomkins used Pounds 12.3m of the Pounds 90.4m provisions set up at the time
of acquisition in the six months to October 30. About Pounds 69m was left,
which would be needed over the next 12 to 18 months.
Spending on advertising had been increased by Pounds 8m to support brands
such as Mr Kipling's cakes, Hovis bread and Sharwoods ethnic foods, which
had been neglected by the old management. New products had been launched,
such as sun-dried tomato bread for Marks and Spencer. Mr Hutchings said the
bread market was no more competitive than, for example, the lawnmower market
in the US.
Mr Ian Duncan, finance director, said Tomkins' operating profits, excluding
RHM, rose from Pounds 39m to Pounds 47.4m, with about Pounds 4m due to the
fall in sterling against the dollar. The group had hedged dollar profits for
the current year at Dollars 1.59 which compared with a rate of Dollars 1.76
for 1992-93.
Profits from North America rose 71 per cent to Pounds 50.1m. Mr Hutchings
said this demonstrated the group's operational gearing, where a rise in
volume led to a sharper rise in profits.
However, in some divisions margins fell as competition was still fierce. Mr
Duncan said that, for instance, at Murray Ohio, the US lawnmowers and
bicycles business, higher volumes had been gained at the expense of lower
margins.
He said the group's net cash had risen to Pounds 169.8m at the end of the
half-year, up from Pounds 120.6m on May 1. But with interest rates low, cash
was 'our worst performing asset'. Interest receivable fell from Pounds 6.3m
to Pounds 4.6m.
After tax, earnings per share rose 23.2 per cent to 5.53p fully diluted. The
interim dividend goes up from 1.805p to 2.08p.
Mr Hutchings said the group had increased interim earnings per share by
three times the market average over the last 10 years and the dividend at 2
1/2 times the average.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
