<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Scandal pushes rock-like imageto the edge: Patrick Harverson
explains how Prudential Securities is being hit by investors' claims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When Prudential Securities agreed to pay Dollars 371m (Pounds 250m) in fines
and restitution to settle charges that it defrauded hundreds of thousands of
investors who bought high-risk limited partnerships from its brokers in the
1980s, the Wall Street firm thought the worst of the scandal was over. Mr
Hardwick Simmons, chief executive, said of the settlement three months ago:
'It's one last punch. The eye already got blackened.'
In the past fortnight, however, the firm received another black eye when Mr
Loren Schechter, its general counsel, was forced to resign. Mr Schechter,
the firm's chief legal officer for more than 11 years, was ousted after it
was reported that the US attorney's office in Manhattan was investigating
the legal department's role in vetting sales documents used in connection
with the partnerships.
Over the next few months several former and current executives, including Mr
George Ball, former chief executive, as well as Mr Schechter, are expected
to be issued with subpoenas by government investigators seeking more
information on the case.
Mr Ball's career has continued to suffer - last October he resigned from a
top post at another Wall Street brokerage, Smith Barney Shearson, amid
speculation that he was asked to go because of the publicity surrounding the
limited partnerships case.
Other indications that the issue has yet to run its course include the
prospect that senior executives at the firm in the 1980s will be charged by
the Securities and Exchange Commission with failing to supervise properly
the brokers selling the partnerships, and the recent naming of Prudential
Insurance, the firm's parent company - and two accounting firms Arthur
Andersen and Deloitte &amp; Touche - in lawsuits involving the limited
partnerships.
The investigation of wrongdoing at Prudential Securities has implications
beyond the firm. The publicity surrounding it has come at a bad time for the
US brokerage industry, which has been trying to fend off accusations that it
was lax in preventing 'rogue brokers' from taking advantage of investors
through unscrupulous trading practices. The longer the Prudential Securities
affair drags on, the harder it will be for Wall Street to convince investors
that its brokers can be trusted.
The problems plaguing Prudential Securities, the fourth largest firm in the
industry, date back to the early 1980s, when brokers at Prudential-Bache
Securities, as the firm was then called, sold about Dollars 8bn of highly
speculative limited partnerships in property, oil and gas investments to
about 400,000 clients.
Although the clients say they had been assured the investments were safe, by
the end of the decade the high-risk investments had soured amid the collapse
of the property and energy markets. Investors were left with billions of
dollars in losses. By the start of the 1990s, thousands of clients had
launched lawsuits against Prudential Securities, claiming they had been
defrauded by brokers who had misled them about the partnerships' risks and
returns. So far, only a few class-action lawsuits on behalf of several
thousand investors have been settled, at a cost to the firm of Dollars 270m.
Prudential Insurance's public image - built upon the advertising slogan
'Solid as a Rock' - has been tarnished by the events, partly because many
investors said they bought the partnerships as they trusted the Prudential
name.
The parent company has also been named in several class-action lawsuits
which claim the insurer was part of a racketeering conspiracy involving the
sale of the partnerships. Government investigators are also looking into
allegations that insurance agents at the parent company bypassed rules that
prohibited them from selling partnerships and other securities.
Prudential Insurance's debt rating might even be lowered because of the
events. Last month the insurance ratings agency AM Best was considering
downgrading the rating from A-double plus, its highest grade, because of
uncertainty surrounding the financial implications of the partnerships
affair.
Ultimately, the biggest cost will be in dollars. To date, the firm has
agreed to pay a total of Dollars 641m to settle SEC charges and class-action
lawsuits. The funds will come out of the Dollars 700m Prudential Securities
has set aside in reserves to cover such costs.
Under the terms of last October's SEC settlement, the firm is obliged to
meet the claims of any of the 400,000 clients who bought the limited
partnerships who can convince lawyers that they were defrauded.
Industry analysts estimate that the firm will need to come up with hundreds
of millions of dollars more. Mr Perrin Long, analyst at First of Michigan,
says: 'My guess is the final bill will be at least Dollars 1bn.' The firm
has admitted the Dollars 700m will grow to at least Dollars 800m.
The only good news for Prudential Securities is that all this has come at a
time when it can afford the huge costs. If it had erupted in the late 1980s,
when the securities industry was struggling, it might have broken the firm.
Today, however, Wall Street is entering the fourth year of boom, and
Prudential Securities has thrived. Yet, the scandal has ruined what should
have been the best years in the firm's history.
While every other big securities firm has been basking in record profits,
Prudential Securities admits it has had to put aside a dollar in its
reserves for every dollar of earnings.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Prudential Securities Group.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6211 Security Brokers and Dealers.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT941-16279</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EAKC0AEAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940111
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Christmas sales up 11% for Signet
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Signet, the jewellery group formerly known as Ratners, defied rumours
circulating last month of poor Christmas trading to announce an 11 per cent
sales increase in December.
Mr James McAdam, chairman and chief executive, said the rise in
like-for-like sales - excluding store openings and closures - in the crucial
Christmas period and a 6 per cent like-for-like increase for the 11 months
to December 31, meant Signet was likely to return to profit after a Pounds
40.1m loss last year. Signet shares gained 3 1/2 p to 31p.
Mr McAdam said the group had maintained the improved gross margin of about
57 per cent achieved in 1992.
'We didn't break ranks and start discounting,' he said. 'The sale didn't
start until after Christmas.'
That, combined with a further reduction in operating costs of about Pounds
30m, in addition to Pounds 50m the previous year, was 'driving the bottom
line hard'. Most analysts are forecasting pre-tax profits of Pounds 1m to
Pounds 2m for the year to January 29, although restoration of the dividend
is unlikely for some time.
The group performance was boosted by a strong showing by its Sterling chain
in the US, which now accounts for 55 per cent of group turnover, and 928 of
its 1,645 jewellery outlets. Sales were up 19 per cent on the previous
December, compared with single-digit rises among most competitors.
In the UK, like-for-like jewellery sales were up 6 per cent in December,
including a 12 per cent rise at Ernest Jones, and 5 per cent at H Samuel.
But sales in the Ratners chain, which now comprises only 100 stores, were
flat. Mr McAdam said the chain would shrink to 60 stores by the middle of
this year, through further conversion of Ratners stores into the H Samuel
format. Ratners stores already converted have enjoyed sales increases of
about 20 per cent.
The remaining 60 stores will be converted to a new format, and may be
renamed. Mr Mc-Adam said the format was likely to be based heavily on
experience gained from 'very encouraging' tests of trial outlets, called
Equa, in Swindon, Norwich and Peterborough.
The 186 Salisburys handbags, luggage and fashion accessories stores
continued to perform badly, with sales down 24 per cent in December. Signet
said a new management was looking at ways of turning the business round.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
