<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Investigation to start into Metallgesellschaft's ex-boss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER and CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Frankfurt prosecutor's office has launched a formal investigation into
Mr Heinz Schimmelbusch, the former chief executive of the troubled
Metallgesellschaft group, and former finance director Mr Meinhard Forster.
Ms Hildegarde Becker-Toussaint, spokeswoman for the office, said the
investigation would focus on suspicion of fraud and failure to inform the
supervisory board of developments.
Metallgesellschaft refused to comment on the investigation yesterday, nor on
press reports that Mr Schimmelbusch, a 49-year-old Austrian, had misused
company funds. If formal charges were brought as a result of the
investigation, the former executives could face fines or up to 10 years in
jail.
The investigation, initiated after a complaint from a Metallgesellschaft
shareholder, follows the sacking of the two executives last month after the
group encountered serious liquidity difficulties arising from its activities
on the US oil futures market.
Since then the scale of the problems afflicting the Frankfurt-based metals
and mining group, has escalated. Last week Mr Kajo Neukirchen, the new chief
executive, revealed that losses in the year to September amounted to DM1.8bn
(Pounds 700m) - five times those originally reported.
The group's bankers and shareholders have been given until tomorrow night to
support a DM2.7bn injection of new equity capital. The group's bank
creditors were told yesterday that they were expected to extend DM700m of
new credit to the company - DM200m more than the figure mentioned at last
week's crisis meeting.
Mr Gunter Rexrodt, German economics minister, urged bank creditors and
shareholders to support a swift restructuring. He said this would secure
jobs and avoid unnecessary tensions on international metals markets.
It is likely the 100-plus banks involved will accept the refinancing. There
is unhappiness among non-German banks over the lack of time for considering
the plans and the rigidity of the proposals.
Banks asked for new credits, Page 24
