<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Consumer credit drop may be obscuring trend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Consumer credit figures for November last year, published by the Central
Statistical Office yesterday, give mixed signals about the recent trends in
consumer spending.
Seasonally adjusted net lending to consumers in November was Pounds 290m,
down from Pounds 312m in October and below analysts' expectations. The main
culprit was finance houses' net lending, which was down to Pounds 262m from
Pounds 349m in October.
However, this contradicts figures from the Finance and Leasing Association,
published at the weekend, which showed an 8 per cent increase in lending
between the October and November figures.
Monthly statistics are always subject to distortion and, if one aggregates
the last three months' figures, the trend in the CSO statistics is positive.
Net lending in the three months to November was Pounds 1.09bn, up from
Pounds 642m in the three months to August and the highest three-monthly
figure since 1989.
The prospect of the November 30 Budget may have temporarily lessened
consumers' desire to spend. Figures for M0, usually a good indicator of
activity in the retail sector, have pointed to a pick-up in spending in late
December.
Figures for finance-house lending show that consumers were prepared to spend
on cars in November. New vehicle-related lending was Pounds 905m, up from
Pounds 758m in October.
November's credit figures show that net lending on bank credit cards picked
up, to Pounds 36m, after consumers repaid Pounds 31m of credit card debt in
October. New credit advanced on bank credit cards in November was a record
of Pounds 2.99bn.
</TEXT>
