<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Labour attacks Tory tax 'hypocrisy'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, yesterday accused the prime minister
of 'hypocrisy and deceit' by scheduling 20 separate tax rises for the next
two years in spite of his party's general election pledge not to raise
taxation.
In the first assault of the new year on the government's economic policy, Mr
Brown outlined what he described as 'the hidden Tory tax calendar' at the
heart of the past two Budgets.
Citing weekend remarks by Mr John Major that the Tory party had no instinct
for tax rises, Mr Brown suggested that, from April this year, there would be
a tax rise every month until the end of 1994. This would, he claimed, amount
to an increase of Pounds 1,330 in tax for the typical family over the next
two years.
It was 'an extraordinary political own goal and an act of hypocrisy, broken
promises and deceit unrivalled in the history of taxation,' Mr Brown said.
He said the tax rises would hit the very groups in society which the
Conservatives had pledged at the last general election to protect from tax
increases. In many cases, he said, the increases would be larger than those
the Tories had suggested would be introduced by a Labour government.
For example, he said, a clinical nurse earning Pounds 13,250 would pay an
extra Pounds 791 in tax. In contrast, a Conservative general election
campaign advertisement had alleged that the extra burden under Labour would
be Pounds 479.
He also said that someone earning Pounds 15,000 a year would pay an extra
Pounds 811 under the proposed tax rises while the Conservatives had claimed
that, under Labour, the total tax rise would have been Pounds 647.
</TEXT>
