<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / BBC to unveil reforms today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The BBC will today unveil a package of fundamental changes to pay,
conditions and grading in an effort to make the corporation more
competitive.
The changes flow from Producer Choice, the internal market in BBC services
launched last year. Producers now have control over their own budgets and
have the right to go outside the corporation to buy services.
The Producer Choice system, it is believed, has demonstrated that some BBC
business units, or departments, are uncompetitive compared with their
private-sector rivals. As a result, a number of managers have been seeking
greater flexibility on everything from pay and conditions to the
corporation's grading system.
The move will be seen as highly controversial by the broadcasting unions
because of the clear implication that a fragmentation of corporation-wide
terms and conditions of employment is about to be unleashed with the
possibility that some staff at least will be offered less attractive terms.
Details of the package are not yet known, but it is clear that the present
system of collective bargaining could be under threat.
The BBC would confirm yesterday only that there had been talks on pay and
conditions. It declined to say anything before today, when the process of
briefing staff will begin.
Apart from some differences in terms in separate business units, it is
believed the package will involve an element of performance-related pay.
Apart from the effects of Producer Choice, which the BBC claims has already
contributed to savings of more than Pounds 100m, the pressure for financial
change at the BBC is coming from the effects of nearly flat licence-fee
income growth and some rising costs.
The years of transition from black-and-white licence fees to colour meant
sustained growth in BBC income in real terms. That process is now complete
although the Government recently agreed that the licence fee would be linked
to retail prices for the last three years of the BBC's existing royal
charter, which runs out at the end of 1996.
Mr John Birt, director-general, promised to turn the BBC into a model public
corporation in Extending Choice, the corporation's vision of its future. Mr
Birt said in a recent interview that Producer Choice had revealed that some
areas were still overmanned and that further redundancies were necessary,
but he declined to say how many.
A government white paper on the future of the BBC is expected in the next
couple of months as part of the decision-making process on the renegotiation
of the corporation's royal charter
In November the BBC said it was seeking to make further efficiency gains of
13 per cent over the next three years and that savings would have to be made
across the board.
</TEXT>
