<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Left seeks to lead Revenue union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The broad left is mounting a serious challenge to capture the top job in the
Inland Revenue Staff Federation, the 57,000-strong tax officers' union.
As a postal ballot for the post of general secretary began yesterday, the
present leader Mr Clive Brooke is coming under attack from Mr John Ellis, a
tax official from Crewe, Cheshire, who sits on the executive.
Mr Ellis is calling for 'an immediate change of direction' in the union by
launching a campaign of lawful industrial action against the government's
plans to market-test and privatise Inland Revenue services.
'The purpose of such a campaign is to force our bosses around a real
negotiating table,' said Mr Ellis, who also wants a shorter working week for
tax officers, increased annual leave, and job security through redeployment.
Mr Ellis is calling for a 'pro-active agenda rather than one where the union
does nothing more than react and accommodate the Inland Revenue's agenda'.
He wants a leadership that 'can relate to members' fears, anger and
aspirations'.
Although Mr Brooke also opposes the government's plans, he argues that
industrial action is 'only one' of many weapons the union can use to defend
its members. He says disruption 'should never be taken for its own sake'
because there is 'no point in winning a glorious defeat'.
'I stand for practical steps to defend members rather than to expose them to
real risks to their jobs,' said Mr Brooke. He added that the union had taken
industrial action over market-testing under his leadership, but had also
sought to persuade the government to change direction.
He said no Revenue staff had suffered compulsory redundancy, national pay
bargaining had been maintained and there had been pay rises, not freezes,
for staff during the past five years.
