<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Milk market reform plan put on shelf
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Plans to open the milk market in England and Wales to competition on April 1
were shelved yesterday. The Milk Marketing Board failed to overcome
remaining government objections to its proposals to become a producer
co-operative.
Postponement of the board's demise was agreed at a meeting between Mr Andrew
Dare, chief executive, and government officials.
'Because of the lead time that we need to make all the necessary
arrangements, we're not going to hit April 1,' said Mr Peter Morgan, the
board's head of corporate affairs.
Time is needed in particular for the partial flotation of Dairy Crest, the
board's dairy products subsidiary, which has to take place first in order to
provide working capital for the new co-operative, Milk Marque.
The board, which for 60 years has bought all milk from farmers in England
and Wales, selling it on to dairy companies, must now propose a new date for
market liberalisation. It is believed to favour July 1.
'We won't want to delay any longer than is necessary, but neither will we
want to rush into putting forward another date if there's a risk we can't
honour it,' said Mr Morgan. The government last month challenged key aspects
of the board's plans, saying they could be anti-competitive.
Questions were raised over the proposed bulk transfer of assets, milk
records and haulage contracts from the board to the new body, the way milk
would be auctioned to dairy companies and the requirement that farmers who
joined Milk Marque should give 12 months' notice if they wanted to leave.
Mrs Gillian Shephard, agriculture minister, moved quickly yesterday to
dispel concern among farmers about the uncertainty that has been created
over the future of milk marketing.
'We have made such good progress on outstanding issues that I'm confident we
shall come to a good agreement,' she said. 'However, the issues raised are
very complex ones affecting 30,000 milk producers, 50m consumers and an
industry valued in billions of pounds.
'The most important thing is to ensure the successor arrangements for the
Milk Marketing Board are right.'
A further meeting will be held on January 24, when both sides hope remaining
problems can be resolved.
