<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Southwark calls in private sector to help rebuild estates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Private-sector developers are involved in radical plans for a
public/private-sector consortium to tackle one of London's most serious
concentrations of poor-quality council housing.
Under the proposals being discussed by Southwark council and the Department
of the Environment, about 1,000 homes in the five south London estates of
North Peckham, Gloucester Grove, Willowbrook, Camden and Sumner could be
demolished. The land would be used to build houses for sale and to rent
through housing associations, with the remaining council homes refurbished.
The comprehensive regeneration project - which involves one of the
highest-density population concentrations in the south-east - would be
financed by capital from the private sector, the Housing Corporation, the
government and the local authority.
Costs are still being worked out, but would be considerable. Proposals in
1990 for refurbishment of Gloucester Grove and North Peckham through a
Housing Action Trust - which would have taken the estates out of
Labour-controlled Southwark council's control - would have cost about Pounds
112m at 1988 prices. The plan was rejected by tenants.
Southwark council and the government are investing Pounds 52m in
improvements at three of the estates, and the council estimates that work at
North Peckham alone will need a further Pounds 48m.
An environment department conference on estate regeneration and the private
sector on Friday will be told that Southwark has successfully interested
private-sector developers - including Barrett and John Laing - in the
possibility of joining a consortium to change the social and economic nature
of the area.
An average of 87 per cent of families are council tenants - rising to 99 per
cent on some estates - and it is planned to reduce this to 60 per cent by
the end of the decade.
The urgent need for a more broadly balanced population on the estates, where
unemployment rates are about 27 per cent, is emphasised in a Southwark
report on the future of the retail centre at Peckham. 'New housing for sale
is vital if Peckham is to stand any chance of retaining its role as a centre
even within the borough,' it says.
Population density would be cut from 438 per hectare to 350 through
substantial demolition of blocks. New homes would be built for sale or rent
through housing associations.
Gloucester Grove and North Peckham estates have presented problems ever
since they were built in the 1970s. They have suffered from inadequate
design and high levels of deprivation and crime.
The estates suffer serious economic and social problems in spite of being
within two miles of central London, which should increase their appeal to
private developers.
The council envisages working with two to four housebuilders and up to six
housing associations. Many residents would have to move to enable the
development to take place.
Mr John Johnson, who chairs Southwark's economic development committee,
said: 'A scheme of this scale would work only with tenants' support, and
they are understandably suspicious. But I think they are also realistic, and
appreciate that there will be few other opportunities for improving the
environment.'
</TEXT>
