<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Tories fail to answer basic questions: A party braced for
further disclosures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's back-to-basics initiative was mired in a philosophical
quagmire yesterday as Tory MPs struggled to agree on a moral framework for
the campaign.
The party appeared deeply split as some ministers insisted the initiative
was not aimed at personal morality, while others said it ought to be.
Ominously for Mr John Major, the prime minister, both rightwing moralists
and normally supportive liberals were saying privately that the issue had
been badly handled.
The party is bracing itself for the possibility of further disclosures about
the private lives of those MPs perceived by elements of the media and some
constituency activists to be guilty of moral turpitude.
To add to Mr Major's problems, MPs return to Westminster today for the start
of a parliamentary session which was always expected to be difficult for the
government.
Moral issues will come under the Commons spotlight early in the session when
MPs debate whether to reduce the age of consent for homosexuals from 21 to
either 18 or 16.
The government will also introduce two controversial law and order measures
 -the Police and Magistrates' Courts bill and the Criminal Justice bill -
described by Mr Major as crucial to back-to-basics.
In addition ministers will have to decide whether to accept demands for
changes to the education bill - another back-to-basics measure - following a
frosty reception in the Lords at the end of the last parliamentary session.
However, the government's most important task will be to agree on a way to
clarify the aims of back-to-basics and defuse attacks by constituency
activists on the behaviour of some MPs.
Ministers were sending confusing signals yesterday, suggesting that the
government is still groping towards a coherent moral framework for the
initiative three months after it was launched at the Conservative party
conference.
Mr Michael Howard, home secretary, said the campaign was 'not about drawing
up a check-list for individual behaviour in every set of circumstances
because that is not something which governments can or should do'.
Mr William Waldegrave, the Citizens' Charter minister, also said the
government had 'better things to do' than to lecture voters on private
morals. But Mr John Redwood, the Welsh secretary, and Mr John Patten,
education secretary, both said moral issues were important to the
government.
Mr Patten said: 'I always feel a child who is brought up without a father
suffers terribly. It doesn't matter whether they are married or not - I
prefer them to be married myself - but I think the fathers should be there.'
But it was this sort of language, employed by rightwing ministers such as Mr
Peter Lilley, social security secretary, and Mr Michael Portillo, chief
secretary to the Treasury, which caused back-to-basics to be seen as a moral
crusade.
Dame Jill Knight, a vice-chairman of the influential 1922 committee of Tory
backbenchers, said moral issues were a 'narrow but extremely important
aspect of responsibility'.
Mr Bill Cash, a leading rightwing critic of the prime minister, said a
policy based on traditional family values was sustainable 'despite the fact
that a number of people seem to have wandered off course'.
There were nervous references at Westminster yesterday to 1963, when the
Profumo scandal did much to prepare the ground for a Labour general election
victory.
For the moment, however, the controversy is merely embarrassing for the
government, rather than dangerous. The spate of disclosures about MPs in the
past week has shaken ministers, but party managers believe the damage can be
contained as long as the revelations end soon.
</TEXT>
<XX>
