<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Press watchdog widens its remit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Press Complaints Commission is to abandon its controversial rule that
stops investigation of most breaches of the newspaper industry's code of
practice when there is no complainant.
The rule has led to embarrassing inconsistencies. Some complaints by third
parties have not been pursued even though, in some cases involving members
of the royal family, the commission has intervened when no complaint has
been made.
The commission will now change its articles of association to make it much
easier to adjudicate on third party complaints.
The issue came to a head over commission plans to appoint Professor Robert
Pinker, one of its members, as privacy commissioner. Prof Pinker will remain
a member and continue to adjudicate on general complaints, but he will also
head any investigations into unnecessary invasions of privacy. He will also
have the right to start his own inquiries. His work will be done under
commission auspices, and he will submit his recommendation to the full
commission.
In extreme cases of breaches of the rules on privacy, the privacy
commissioner will be able to recommend that publishers take disciplinary
action against the editors responsible.
The move is the response of the newspaper industry to complaints from Mr
Peter Brooke, the national heritage secretary.
Following the Daily Mirror's publication of unauthorised pictures of the
Princess of Wales exercising in a gym, Mr Brooke said stronger measures were
needed to protect privacy although he accepted that the self-regulatory body
had performed well in dealing with press inaccuracies.
Mr Brooke said at the time that the government would 'take into account the
failure that has occurred' over the Mirror affair when examining the scope
for criminal or civil remedies to protect personal privacy.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
    P2711 Newspapers.
</IN>
