<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Business failures 'show 46% fall'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The number of UK business failures in the final quarter of 1993 fell to the
lowest level since 1989, say estimates released yesterday by Trade
Indemnity, the credit insurance group.
Failures encountered by Trade Indemnity's policyholders fell by 46 per cent
in the fourth quarter compared with the same period in 1992. The group
registered 942 business failures in the final three months of 1993, a 21 per
cent fall on the previous quarter.
Trade Indemnity said the figures showed a radical change in the UK business
climate. 'Whilst there is usually a seasonal increase in the first quarter
of the new year, it is clear that companies are at last able to concentrate
their minds on expansion rather than simply survival,' the company said.
Trade Indemnity warned that companies' cashflow still remained under
pressure. 'The overriding message from our policyholders at present is one
of margins continuing to be squeezed between price pressure from customers
and higher-cost supplies.'
The company said its statistics tended to reflect failure trends of more
established companies. It said evidence suggested its statistics often led
other available indicators by as much as six months.
Trade statistics, Page 10
</TEXT>
