<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Country town gets terminal fever as high-tech telecentre
takes off: Paul Cheeseright monitors the progress of an attempt to stimulate
a local economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Gill Lowes popped four doors down Kington High Street from Howard and
Palmer, the chemists, and into the telecentre, now labelled Kington
Connected Community Project, to hire a laptop computer for the weekend. She
is trying to work up a database of nutrition information which, she hopes,
will find a commercial application.
Mr Sam Llewellyn, author of Riptide, Clawhammer and other thrillers, sat
inside the centre at a computer terminal he was using for about Pounds 3.50
an hour. Apart from novel-writing he has a little publishing business. 'The
telecentre facilitates that immensely - you can do the design, the
typesetting, the lot yourself,' he said.
The telecentre in Kington, Hereford and Worcester, stuffed with more than
Pounds 250,000 of electronics, has in three months become the focal point
for the Connected Community Project - the shop window of the attempt to
stimulate the economy of a small country town by the application of the
latest high-technology.
The leading partners in this experiment of creating an electronic community
are the Department of Trade and Industry and the Rural Development
Commission, both of whose motives are to foster economic growth. Other
leading partners are British Telecommunications and Apple Computer, which
are looking for new ways of selling equipment and services.
Kitting out the telecentre is a continuing business. 'We've done something
called future proofing. As equipment gets faster this network won't get
outdated,' explained Mr Keith Harris, Kington's technical director.
The installation of cabling and equipment has been done to make future
change easy. 'You don't have to rewire the building to change the position
of a telephone,' he said.
The telecentre has drawn the curious to such an extent that, to allow the
serious to carry on working, it is now closed during the mornings for those
dropping in casually.
'We expected the level of interest in the centre would grow organically, but
it's been a bang,' said Mr Miles Swinburne, the Kington project manager.
'We're having to introduce booking times.'
Word processing and desktop-publishing courses, taking place at the
telecentre until a full-scale training centre can be set up, are three-times
subscribed. Youngsters are coming in on Saturday mornings. 'We're teaching
the kids to build a picture,' said Mr Lawrence Smith, a local art teacher.
Anybody with the right equipment at home can pay a subscription, link with
centre, be given storage space in the telecentre's computers and become part
of the electronic mailing system.
The telecentre is also a gateway to the the world through BT's newly
installed Integrated Services Digital Network - phone lines which can
transmit almost instantaneously text, data, voice and image.
The development of the centre, after of public meetings in Kington last
summer extolling the potential benefits of a high-technology infusion,
created expectations which Mr Swinburne and Mr Harris, the only two people
paid full-time by the project company, cannot easily meet.
The project has 34 Macintosh computers provided by Apple but, said Mr
Swinburne: 'People believed we had 100 machines in a cupboard and we are
mean bastards not letting them out.'
Of those 34 machines, 16 are in the telecentre, six are destined for the
training room, and six are in local schools. For the rest, progress in
getting them installed and running around the community has been slower than
Mr Swinburne had expected during the planning days of last summer.
This is partly explained by the concentration of effort on the telecentre
and partly by delays in the training of those who will use them in the first
instance.
Three machines, for example, will be used by a chain of local sports shops
to control stocks, but the retailers themselves have had to concentrate on
the Christmas trade rather than computer training.
But the work of finding computer applications relevant to the economic
development and commercial growth of Kington has not stopped.
Just as Ms Lowes is trying to work up her nutrition database, so Ms Ann
Pollock is working on a tourism project which would computerise and make
available according to demand information such as traffic flows and future
local attractions. Mr Richard Hammond is working on the computerisation of
farm accounts.
Now that the project is moving out of the teething-trouble phase, the method
of funding it has started to change. Kington Connected Community is
dependent not just on the four main sponsors but also on the Hereford and
Worcestershire Training and Enterprise Council and the Leominster District
Council.
'They're moving quickly from chucking money in the pot to project-driven
funding,' said Mr Swinburne, citing work that the project has received from
the district council to computerise information for housing-tenants
associations.
But, against the background of a so far feeble revenue stream, he warned
that 'all documentation on this tells you it takes about three years to be
self-financing'.
Technology, Page 13
</TEXT>
