<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Institutions to finance lottery bid by Rank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Rank Organisation plans to bid for the National Lottery licence with
finance largely provided by a consortium of institutional investors.
Mr Michael Gifford, chief executive of the leisure group, has reached
agreement in principle with a range of large UK institutions, said to be
household names.
If it won the licence Rank would be the operating company. It would probably
hold a minority of the equity, and choose all suppliers by tender.
Although Rank is a serious contender, it is unlikely to announce formally
its intention to bid much before the February 14 deadline.
Meanwhile Ladbroke, the hotel and leisure group, and MAI, the television,
financial services and market research group, confirmed their intention to
bid, unveiling a heavyweight board for the joint venture known as Games For
Good Causes.
Mr Malcolm Hughes, managing director of Vernons, the Ladbroke-owned football
pools company, will be chief executive of the lottery consortium.
He said yesterday that the National Lottery might eventually raise nearly
Pounds 1bn a year for good causes and Pounds 500m for taxpayers. This
implies annual revenues of about Pounds 4bn.
He also promised that, if successful, the operation would be based in
Liverpool, home of Vernons, although it would be independent of the pools
organisation.
The consortium is chaired by Sir Christopher Benson, chairman of Boots. Lord
Hesketh, former government chief whip in the Lords, is deputy chairman.
The board also includes Sir Michael Lickiss, a senior partner in Grant
Thornton, the accountants, Sir Michael Jenkins, an executive director of
Kleinwort Benson, and Ms Elizabeth Filkin, the Inland Revenue's independent
adjudicator, who would act as a lottery ombudsman.
Ladbroke and MAI would each take a third of the equity with the rest being
offered to institutional investors.
All the consortium's technology would be supplied by the UK subsidiary of
AT&amp;T/NCR, the communications and computing group, which would draw on the
lottery equipment of Automated Wagering International of the US.
Sir Christopher said yesterday that the consortium was 'looking at a high
street operation' but declined to say whether this might include Boots. He
promised Games For Good Causes intended to be 'as open as we can' on its
application after the bids have gone in.
Eight consortia have so far indicated serious plans to bid for the lottery
licence with signs of two further 'dark horses' in the wings.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
