<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Gas price rise hits big users
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Gas is to raise the price of one and two-year interruptible gas
contracts by an average 6 per cent from next month.
Interruptible contracts enable large consumers to buy gas at cheaper rates.
They do so in the knowledge that they might be cut off at short notice.
There are about 1,000 customers in the interruptible market, some of them
the largest gas consumers in the country, including power stations.
Mr Norman Blacker, director of the UK gas business, said factory gate prices
had increased by 9 per cent over the past two years, but interruptible
prices had fallen by more than 25 per cent in real terms since British Gas
was privatised in 1986.
'It is important that our prices in this market become more
cost-reflective,' he said.
British Gas has been told by its regulators to allow more competition in the
contract market.
But though it has now lost 70 per cent of the firm contract business,
competitors have been slow to offer interruptible contracts because they
believe that British Gas prices have been too low.
This price increase, which has been agreed with Ofgas, the regulator, should
stimulate more competitor interest.
</TEXT>
