<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / French inflation down to 2.1%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Weak domestic demand and seasonal factors prompted a fall in French consumer
price inflation in December, according to figures released yesterday by
Insee, the national statistics office.
Consumer prices fell by 0.1 per cent compared with November, giving an
annual rate of inflation of 2.1 per cent.
Insee said that a slight fall in the consumer price index was not unusual at
the end of the year and reflected a fall in prices in fruit and vegetables
and in clothing. Additional factors included a reduction in the price of oil
products.
Economists in Paris said that the weakness of inflation also reflected
fragile consumer demand in the face of uncertain economic growth and the
rise in unemployment. Several economists estimate that consumer spending
fell in the final quarter of 1993, after rising strongly, by 0.7 per cent,
in the third quarter.
