<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / IG Farben assets case dismissed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A German court said yesterday that IG Farben, a shell company handling the
liquidation of the notorious second world war Nazi chemicals cartel, has no
legal claim to dispossessed assets in eastern Germany, Reuter reports from
Berlin.
The federal administrative court in Berlin confirmed an earlier ruling by a
lower court in Halle.
IG Farben shareholders had hoped to gain millions of marks in windfall
profits from the sale of the company's property in east Germany.
IG Farben, which developed the gas used to kill millions in Nazi death
camps, was broken up afterwards and formed the nucleus of Germany's three
main chemical groups Hoechst, BASF and Bayer.
