<DATE>940111
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Tory MPs attack PM over 'back to basics'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major's handling of the back to basics controversy was under fire
yesterday as the issue of the private lives of Conservative MPs threw the
government into deeper disarray.
MPs on all sides of the Tory party said the prime minister had mishandled
the backlash which forced Mr Tim Yeo to resign as an environment minister
over an affair which produced an illegitimate daughter.
The government's difficulties were compounded by the resignation of Lord
Caithness, a senior government spokesman in the Lords, following the
apparent suicide of his wife. A post-mortem confirmed that Lady Caithness
died from a single gunshot wound to the head.
Mr John Patten, the education secretary, admitted in a radio interview that
the government had been battered by the events of the past week. 'I cannot
remember a time since I have been in the House when it has been so
difficult,' he added.
MPs were split over whether Mr Major should have stood by Mr Yeo to
demonstrate his tolerance, or fired him to demonstrate the government's
commitment to family values. There was widespread agreement that his
decision to do neither has deprived the back to basics initiative of a clear
moral framework.
One influential rightwing back bencher said the government appeared to have
been caught trying to 'duck and weave and fudge issues' instead of offering
decisive moral leadership.
One cabinet minister applauded the prime minister's stand against a 'witch
hunt' for moral nonconformists, but accused him of failing to make clear
judgments about the values involved in back to basics.
The confusion was also reflected in ministerial statements intended to
support Mr Major's weekend assertion that the initiative was mainly
concerned with education and crime. Mr Michael Howard, home secretary, said
the campaign 'does not involve hectoring. It does not involve those matters
which are more the responsibility of the pulpit than politicians'.
But Mr Patten said the government should stand by its commitment to 'family
responsibility'.
Basic questions, Page 9
Joe Rogaly, Page 16
</TEXT>
