<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 94 / Resignation blow to City watchdog
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The creation of a Personal Investment Authority, the planned City watchdog,
suffered a fresh setback yesterday when one of its directors resigned in
protest at the composition of the board.
The move by Mr Jim Stretton, deputy managing director of Standard Life, was
backed by his company, which became the third leading life office to oppose
publicly the plans for the authority.
The setting up of the PIA, a self-regulatory body for retail financial
services, has met a series of obstacles. The damage from yesterday's events
is more serious because the PIA had previously been gaining momentum amid
growing recognition in the financial services industry that the authority
would come into effect around the middle of this year.
Its creation is central to the plans set out by Mr Andrew Large, the
chairman of the Securities and Investments Board, for enhancing investor
protection.
Mr Stretton said his resignation arose from the board's decision that only
nine of the 19 directors should be active industry practitioners.
The board decided just before Christmas that the other directors should
comprise nine public interest directors and the authority's chief executive.
Mr Joe Palmer, the PIA chairman, regretted Mr Stretton's decision and paid
tribute to his contribution to PIA's development over the past year.
Privately, another board member described Mr Stretton's departure as 'a
major blow'.
Mr Stretton argued that since the industry would be in a minority on the
board, the organisation could not be a self-regulatory body, and that the
preferable route would be to move to statutory regulation.
Mr Roy Nicolson, chief executive of Scottish Amicable, has expressed similar
concerns.
Mr Mick Newmarch, chief executive of Prudential, the UK's largest life
office, has already made clear his preference for statutory regulation and
yesterday said he was interested to see the conclusions 'people we regard as
sensible' had reached.
The SIB, the City's chief regulator, is expected to receive a document next
month on the PIA's plans, and other life offices may wait until that has
been published before making their views known. If they intervene in similar
terms, then the prospect of a confrontation between the industry and the
regulator will intensify.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
