<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JAN 94 / World Bond Markets: New York
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The US bond market, buoyed on Friday by helpful employment figures for
December, will be looking for good inflation statistics this week to bolster
its positive new tone.
The market rallied strongly on Friday on the release of figures that showed
payrolls rising by 183,000 in December. This was well short of the figures
that Wall Street had been expecting.
The statistics suggested that the US economy grew at a moderate pace in the
month, ameliorating fears that November's fast growth would be sustained, in
turn leading to a higher rate of inflation and early action by the Federal
Reserve to raise interest rates.
The 30-year-issue ended the week with a yield of 6.22 per cent - the lowest
it has been since December 23, and down from 6.41 on Monday, which marked a
4 1/2 -month high.
Analysts expect this positive backdrop to be reinforced by very small
increases in the inflation indices for December.
The producer price index, which is due on Wednesday, is expected to show no
rise in the price of finished goods.
The consumer index, which is due on Thursday, is forecast to show a 0.2 per
cent increase, or 0.3 per cent in the core index, which ignores volatile
food and energy prices.
</TEXT>
